title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)

communications.subject: North Dakota Open Records Law Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Dakota Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Ohio Medical Board
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. All physician disciplinary actions from 2019-2024 related to:
   - Mental health conditions
   - Substance use
   - Behavioral health issues

2. Board policies regarding physician health programs

3. Statistics on:
   - Self-reported vs. discovered cases
   - Return to practice rates
   - Appeal outcomes
   
4. Any studies or reports on physician mental health programs

5. Details about Illinois Professionals Health Program (IPHP):
   - Relationship/agreements with medical board
   - Confidentiality policies
   - Rate of board reporting
   - Statistics on physician outcomes
   - Any formal or informal agreements between IPHP and board

6. Any evaluations or audits of IPHP effectiveness

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

communications.subject: Response to Public Records Request
communications.communication:
Mr. Sinclair:

Your public records request submitted to the State Medical Board of Ohio was forwarded to me for response.  You requested:

1. All physician disciplinary actions from 2019-2024 related to:
- Mental health conditions
- Substance use
- Behavioral health issues

2. Board policies regarding physician health programs

3. Statistics on:
- Self-reported vs. discovered cases
- Return to practice rates
- Appeal outcomes

4. Any studies or reports on physician mental health programs

5. Details about Illinois Professionals Health Program (IPHP):
- Relationship/agreements with medical board
- Confidentiality policies
- Rate of board reporting
- Statistics on physician outcomes
- Any formal or informal agreements between IPHP and board

6. Any evaluations or audits of IPHP effectiveness


With respect to Request No. 1, attached please find a listing of the physician disciplinary actions taken by the State Medical Board of Ohio from 2019-2024 related to mental health conditions, substance use and behavioral health issues.  Copies of the disciplinary actions are available on the Medical Board's website at https://elicense.ohio.gov/oh_verifylicense

With respect to Request No. 2, attached please find materials reviewed and approved by the Medical Board's Compliance Committee related to the Ohio Professionals Health Program, including the One-Bite Program and Confidential Monitoring Program.  Information regarding the Medical Board's Impairment Modernization is available on the Medical Board's website at https://med.ohio.gov/for-licensees/treatment-and-compliance/impairment-modernization-parent/impairment-modernization


With respect to Request No. 3, attached please find compliance statistics.  The Board does not keep statistics related to self-reported v. discovered rates or appeal outcomes.

With respect to Request No. 4, attached please find information presented to the Medical Board's Compliance Committee regarding the Ohio Professionals Health Program and the OPHP Well Being Survey.

Requests 5 and 6 are denied because the State Medical Board of Ohio does not maintain any documentation regarding the Illinois Professionals Health Program.

This completes your public records request in its entirety.

Kimberly C. Anderson

communications.subject: RE: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Ohio Medical Board
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Anderson,

Thank you again for your exceptionally thorough and professional response to our public records request. Your office’s transparency and attention to detail — especially in providing internal memos, compliance statistics, and documents on the One-Bite and Confidential Monitoring Programs — stands in stark contrast to the approach taken by many other states. We’re sincerely grateful for your willingness to engage so substantively.

The internal memos you provided reflect a thoughtful, evolving understanding of physician impairment — particularly your recognition that models like One-Bite may discourage physicians from seeking help. The move toward a Confidential Monitoring Program with expanded eligibility, nuanced relapse handling, and clinical discretion is a promising step that other jurisdictions would do well to study.

As part of our ongoing national research initiative on PHP structures and board oversight, I would like to respectfully submit a brief follow-up request for materials that speak directly to program effectiveness and accountability — a key area where many states (even those with strong intentions) still lack meaningful insight:

1. Program Evaluations or Effectiveness Reviews
While the provided statistics are invaluable, we did not locate any:

Formal internal or external audits of OPHP program effectiveness.

Outcome tracking data (e.g., long-term return to practice, relapse rates, recidivism).

Physician feedback or satisfaction surveys regarding the program.

If any summaries, reports, evaluations, or even raw de-identified data exist, we would be very grateful for the opportunity to review them.

2. Appeal and Oversight Structures
Could you clarify:

Whether participants in the Confidential Monitoring Program have any avenues for appeal or recourse if they are found ineligible or removed from the program.

How OPHP determinations are reviewed, audited, or overseen, either by the Medical Board or a third-party body.

3. Contracts and Meeting Minutes
Lastly, if available, we respectfully request:

A copy of the contract, agreement, or MOU between OPHP and the State Medical Board of Ohio.

Any meeting minutes or internal policy discussions (from 2019–2024) where OPHP program performance, reforms, or challenges were reviewed.

We are not requesting names or identifying details and welcome redacted versions as needed.

Again, thank you for the exemplary transparency already shown. We’re grateful for your leadership and the Board’s evolving approach to protecting public safety while supporting physician wellness. Please don’t hesitate to reach out if any portion of this follow-up needs clarification.

Warm regards,

communications.subject: Response to Public Records Request
communications.communication:
Mr. Sinclair:

Your public records request submitted to the State Medical Board of Ohio was forwarded to me for review.  You requested the following regarding OhioPHP and the Board's Confidential Monitoring Program:


  1.  Program Evaluations or Effectiveness Reviews including formal internal or external audits of OPHP program effectiveness; outcome tracking data (e.g. long-term return to practice, relapse rates, recidivism); and physician feedback or satisfaction surveys regarding the program;
  2.  Appeal and Oversight Structures, including whether participants in the Confidential Monitoring Program have any avenues for appeal or recourse if they are found ineligible or removed from the program; and how OPHP determinations are reviewed, audited or overseen either by the Medical Board or a third-party body;
  3.  Contracts and Meeting Minutes, including a copy of the contract, agreement, or MOU between OPHP and the State Medical Board of Ohio and any meeting minutes or internal policy discussions from 2019 through 2024 where OPHP program performance, reforms or challenges were reviewed.
With respect to request number 1, attached please find the Special Program Report covering October 2023 through December 2024, for the first year of the Confidential Monitoring Program.  The Medical Board does not have any responsive documents regarding physician feedback or satisfaction surveys.

With respect to request number 2, the State Medical Board does not have any responsive documents regarding a participant's appeal of a decision to OhioPHP.  For individuals who are found ineligible for the Confidential Monitoring Program and referred to the State Medical Board, all formal disciplinary proceedings would be conducted in accordance with the Medical Board's laws and rules and Chapter 119 of the Ohio Revised Code regarding administrative appeals. communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: New Mexico SEA response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the New Mexico Department of Education sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: USTDA historical reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Internal communications, including but not limited to emails, memos, and directives regarding any removal, modification, or restriction to public access of all available historical reports, dating back to 2020, that were previously housed online in the USTDA Library: https://www.ustda.gov/ustda-library.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kelly Kauffman

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maine Freedom of Access Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by 1 M.R.S.A. § 408(6). The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
The Maine Department of Corrections has received your request for information under the Maine Freedom of Access Act (FOAA).  Your request will be evaluated to determine if it comes within the FOAA, if it is clear as to what information you are requesting, and if nonconfidential records already exist that would fulfill all or part of your request.  If your request does not come within the FOAA, is not clear, or no records exist, you will be so notified.  If records exist, but they are confidential, you will be notified of the basis for that determination.  If nonconfidential records exist, you will be provided a good faith, nonbinding estimate of the time within which you will be provided the records, as well as an estimate of the costs that are allowed by the FOAA, if applicable.

V/r

Jenna Heald
Maine Department of Corrections
Policy & PowerDMS Assistant
FOAA Coordinator

communications.subject: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Child welfare predictive analytics systems
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) Contracts with any company, nonprofit, or other entity that currently provides software to the department that includes predictive analytics models for child welfare (i.e., models designed to identify home placement risk, abuse risk, human trafficking risk, etc.). This should include contracts for CCWIS or comparable systems that include predictive models as well as project descriptions for any models created in-house.

2) Data dictionaries for all child welfare predictive models used by the department, including those provided by outside entities as well as in-house models. Data dictionaries are  documents commonly created for predictive models and databases. They describe the categories of data that are inputs (age, gender, etc.) and outputs (risk level, etc.) of predictive models. They are equivalent to headers on a spreadsheet, and do not include actual data.

3) A list of all memorandums of understanding (MOUs) and/or data sharing agreements with state or local agencies for the provision of data that is incorporated into the department's child welfare predictive models. Should the department not maintain a list of these MOUs, I will accept copies of the MOUs themselves.

4) Any differential impact assessments, validation studies, or comparable documents that describe the accuracy of child welfare predictive models used by the department. This should include any documents that describe common measures of predictive accuracy, such as area under the curve (AUC).

5) All department policies, employee manuals, and guidelines describing how employees can and/or should use child welfare predictive models. 

6) All governance board, committee, or outside expert reviews assessing the efficacy of the department's proposed or current child welfare predictive models.

Should you have questions regarding any aspect of this request, please don't hesitate to contact me.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to use the requested records to publish articles in the public interest. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employ involved and an explanation justifying the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of it, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

I would prefer the request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you very much for your help, and I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: RE: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Child welfare predictive analytics systems
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Arizona Public Records Law request, copied below, and originally submitted on April 30, 2021. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.  This communication was originally to DCSRecordsRequest@azdes.gov. Please see the following request. 
---
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) Contracts with any company, nonprofit, or other entity that currently provides software to the department that includes predictive analytics models for child welfare (i.e., models designed to identify home placement risk, abuse risk, human trafficking risk, etc.). This should include contracts for CCWIS or comparable systems that include predictive models as well as project descriptions for any models created in-house.

2) Data dictionaries for all child welfare predictive models used by the department, including those provided by outside entities as well as in-house models. Data dictionaries are documents commonly created for predictive models and databases. They describe the categories of data that are inputs (age, gender, etc.) and outputs (risk level, etc.) of predictive models. They are equivalent to headers on a spreadsheet, and do not include actual data.

3) A list of all memorandums of understanding (MOUs) and/or data sharing agreements with state or local agencies for the provision of data that is incorporated into the department's child welfare predictive models. Should the department not maintain a list of these MOUs, I will accept copies of the MOUs themselves.

4) Any differential impact assessments, validation studies, or comparable documents that describe the accuracy of child welfare predictive models used by the department. This should include any documents that describe common measures of predictive accuracy, such as area under the curve (AUC).

5) All department policies, employee manuals, and guidelines describing how employees can and/or should use child welfare predictive models.

6) All governance board, committee, or outside expert reviews assessing the efficacy of the department's proposed or current child welfare predictive models.

Should you have questions regarding any aspect of this request, please don't hesitate to contact me.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to use the requested records to publish articles in the public interest. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employ involved and an explanation justifying the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of it, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

I would prefer the request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you very much for your help, and I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the
following records:

1) Contracts with any company, nonprofit, or other entity that
currently provides software to the department that includes
predictive analytics models for child welfare (i.e., models
designed to identify home placement risk, abuse risk, human
trafficking risk, etc.). This should include contracts for CCWIS
or comparable systems that include predictive models as well as
project descriptions for any models created in-house.

2) Data dictionaries for all child welfare predictive models used
by the department, including those provided by outside entities
as well as in-house models. Data dictionaries are documents
commonly created for predictive models and databases. They
describe the categories of data that are inputs (age, gender,
etc.) and outputs (risk level, etc.) of predictive models. They
are equivalent to headers on a spreadsheet, and do not include
actual data.

3) A list of all memorandums of understanding (MOUs) and/or data
sharing agreements with state or local agencies for the provision
of data that is incorporated into the department's child welfare
predictive models. Should the department not maintain a list of
these MOUs, I will accept copies of the MOUs themselves.

4) Any differential impact assessments, validation studies, or
comparable documents that describe the accuracy of child welfare
predictive models used by the department. This should include any
documents that describe common measures of predictive accuracy,
such as area under the curve (AUC).

5) All department policies, employee manuals, and guidelines
describing how employees can and/or should use child welfare
predictive models.

6) All governance board, committee, or outside expert reviews
assessing the efficacy of the department's proposed or current
child welfare predictive models.

Should you have questions regarding any aspect of this request,
please don't hesitate to contact me.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to
use the requested records to publish articles in the public
interest. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a
detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each
employ involved and an explanation justifying the employee hours
required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of
it, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory
exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to
withhold each/any portions from public review.

I would prefer the request be filled electronically, by e-mail
attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you very much for your help, and I look forward to
receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Larry Flynt (FBI)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all documents or FBI files pertaining, or mentioning to Larry Flynt, a pornographic magazine entrepreneur most notable for his production of "Hustler" Magazine. According to news reports, Mr. Flynt died in February of 2021 (https://apnews.com/article/larry-flynt-dead-0ae38f6dca115aed20cb88d5fc547e99) and therefore neither FOIA's b6 exemption nor the Privacy Act relate to him. See also the supporting documentation. His DOB was November 1, 1942 and he died on February 10, 2021.

The request is being made my a member of the news media and I plan to use the original documents and my editorial skills to turn the raw materials into a distinct work. I further intend to distribute my work and the documents to a general audience.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emily Crose

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1501812-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request #G021041-051525
communications.communication:
Hi Mr. Duff,

Thank you for your reply and for clarifying that mental health services are contracted out.

I completely understand that GDC may not employ those providers directly. That said, I’m wondering if GDC could share the name and contact information of any internal staff member responsible for overseeing or coordinating mental health programming at the agency level — such as a program services director, behavioral health liaison, or the contract manager for the mental health services provider.

We’re emailing on behalf of a nonprofit that conducts free, volunteer-led mindfulness and emotional resilience program for inmates and would appreciate any guidance or referral you can offer.

Thanks again for your time and support.

Warm regards,
Andrew Ma

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III."

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

communications.subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

As discussed in our letter of December 6, 2023, we are providing the records we currently have available in response to your June 16, 2023, request.  They are located at the website below:

MuckRock - Julia Rock<https://nmgov-my.sharepoint.com/:f:/r/personal/renee_garcia_erb_nm_gov/Documents/MuckRock%20-%20Julia%20Rock?csf=1&web=1&e=4gwfSH>

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Correction)

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Correction)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Andrew Ma.

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All physician disciplinary actions from 2019-2024 related to:
   - Mental health conditions
   - Substance use
   - Behavioral health issues

2. Board policies regarding physician health programs

3. Statistics on:
   - Self-reported vs. discovered cases
   - Return to practice rates
   - Appeal outcomes
   
4. Any studies or reports on physician mental health programs

5. Details about Maryland Professional Rehabilitation Program (MPRP):
   - Relationship/agreements with medical board
   - Confidentiality policies
   - Rate of board reporting
   - Statistics on physician outcomes
   - Any formal or informal agreements between MPRP and board

6. Any evaluations or audits of MPRP effectiveness

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Anderson:
Thank you for your response dated March 4, 2025, to our Public Information Act request concerning physician disciplinary actions, health programs, and the Maryland Professional Rehabilitation Program (MPRP).
I am writing on behalf of a research organization, which is conducting nationwide research on physician health programs and rehabilitation systems. This research will culminate in a published book documenting how each state handles these critical matters of public health and professional oversight.
While I appreciate your prompt response, I have significant concerns about the transparency limitations revealed in your letter:

Disciplinary Action Data: Although you indicate the Board only tracks complaints by disciplinary grounds, this approach creates a concerning gap in understanding how mental health and substance abuse issues affect physician practice. Even if the data isn't categorized exactly as requested, would it be possible to provide the raw disciplinary data you do have? Our research team has expertise in analyzing such information to identify relevant patterns.
Absence of Information: It is surprising that the Board maintains "no information responsive" to four of our six requests, particularly regarding physician health programs. This suggests a potential gap in oversight that may be worth addressing at the policy level.
MPRP Information: Rather than simply redirecting us to the Office of Contract Management and Procurement (OCMP), would your office be willing to facilitate this connection or provide a specific contact person? As a state-sponsored program affecting physician licensure, greater coordination between agencies would benefit the public interest.

Our book will document how each state responds to these requests, highlighting both exemplary transparency practices and areas for improvement. 
We would welcome the opportunity to revise our request in a way that might yield more substantive information, or to discuss alternative approaches to obtaining this important data. Public understanding of physician health programs serves both the medical community and patient safety.
Please feel free to contact me directly at [phone/email] if you would like to discuss how we might work together more productively on this matter.
Sincerely,

communications.subject: Re: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
Good day Mr. Sinclair,

The MD Board of Physicians (the Board) received a Public Information Act
request from you dated February 13, 2025, and responded to your request on
March 4, 2025, which you acknowledged receiving in your email dated April
18, 2025.

To reiterate, in the PIA response letter to you dated March 4, 2025, the
Board did not provide any records responsive to your request.  In your
follow-up email, you ask if it's possible to receive our complaint data in
a "raw" format that your research team would then analyze to identify
relevant patterns.  Under Maryland PIA laws, the Board's investigative
records, which include complaints, are confidential and prohibited from
public inspection.  Disclosure of these records is prohibited under GP §
4-301(a)(2)(i).  This provision of the PIA prohibits disclosure of a record
when disclosure is contrary to a state statute.  In this case, section
§14-411(b) of the Maryland Medical Practice Act expressly prohibits the
Board, a disciplinary panel, or any of its investigatory bodies from
disclosing any information contained in a record. Furthermore, all
disclosable, public information regarding disciplinary actions against
licensees is available for viewing on the Board's website
<https://www.mbp.state.md.us/sanctions.aspx>.

For items two through six, you requested information on statistical data,
studies, policies, audits, reports on physician health programs, and
specifically the Maryland Physician Health Program (previously referred to
as MPRP).  Again, the Board has no information responsive to your request.
The MPHP
<https://www.mbp.state.md.us/resource_information/res_pro/resource_Practitioner_rehab_volunteer.aspx>
is a voluntary, independent program not affiliated with the Board, as
stated on our website. You were also directed to the resources to contact
regarding your request for details on the relationship/agreement between
MPHP and the Board.

*Pursuant to GP §4-362, you are entitled to seek judicial review of this
decision.  You may also refer any concerns about this decision to the
Public Access Ombudsman in accordance with GP § 4-1B-01 et seq.*

Sincerely,

Rhonda Anderson
Maryland Board of Physicians
CHRC, License Renewal & Customer Service Unit
410-764-4705

customer service.  Please click here

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
To Rhonda Anderson and the Maryland Board of Physicians:
Re: Appeal of PIA Response dated May 7, 2025
I am writing to challenge the Board's continued refusal to provide meaningful information in response to my Public Information Act request dated February 13, 2025.
Your latest response mischaracterizes both my request and Maryland law in several critical ways:

False Claim of Independence: You assert that the Maryland Physician Health Program (MPHP) is "a voluntary, independent program not affiliated with the Board." This claim is demonstrably false. The MPHP is explicitly referenced in COMAR 10.32.22 as a "rehabilitation program" approved by the Board. By law, the Board must maintain documentation of this approval relationship. Your denial of any responsive records suggests either regulatory negligence or deliberate concealment.
Misapplication of Confidentiality Provisions: While MD Code, Gen. Prov. § 4-301(a)(2)(i) and Medical Practice Act § 14-411(b) protect individual case information, they do NOT exempt aggregate statistical data, policies, or contractual agreements from disclosure. Your blanket citation of these provisions without distinguishing between protected individual records and disclosable administrative documents reflects a concerning overreach of confidentiality provisions.
Failure to Segregate Disclosable Information: Maryland PIA requires agencies to separate exempt from non-exempt material rather than withholding entire categories of documents. Your failure to identify which specific records exist but are being withheld, versus which genuinely don't exist, violates both the letter and spirit of the PIA.
Public Interest Considerations: The Maryland Court of Appeals has consistently held that PIA exemptions must be "narrowly construed" in favor of disclosure, particularly when matters of public health and governance are concerned. The Board's relationship with MPHP directly impacts both physician welfare and patient safety - core public interests that outweigh generalized confidentiality claims.
Comparison to Other State Practices: The North Carolina Medical Board, responding to an identical request, provided comprehensive documentation of its relationship with its physician health program, statistical reports, and procedural documents - all without compromising individual confidentiality. Maryland's refusal to provide even basic policy documentation stands in stark contrast to this model of transparency.

Your suggestion that my only recourse is judicial review or an Ombudsman complaint reflects an unfortunate unwillingness to engage substantively with legitimate public interest concerns.
I respectfully request that the Board:

Immediately provide all contracts, MOUs, or agreements between the Board and MPHP
Release redacted versions of policies or procedural documents governing referrals to MPHP
Produce aggregate statistical information that does not identify individual physicians
Provide any audits or evaluations of the MPHP program's effectiveness

If the Board maintains its refusal to provide any responsive documents whatsoever, I request written certification from the Executive Director personally attesting that the Board maintains absolutely no documentation of its relationship with a program explicitly referenced in its own regulations.
I look forward to your response within 10 business days. Please be advised that I am simultaneously filing a complaint with the Public Access Ombudsman and exploring options for judicial review as suggested in your communication.
Sincerely,
Vig Sinclair
cc: Maryland Public Access Ombudsman
Maryland Attorney General's Office, Open Government Division

communications.subject: DC Freedom of Information Act Request: DC DOC transgender policies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the DC Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All department policy and guidance documents regarding transgender inmates, including but not limited to gender-affirming medical care, housing and treatment by staff. I also request records of any proposed and/or enacted changes to said policies made on or after Nov. 6, 2024 until date of search, if such documents exist.

I request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

This is the response of the DC Department of Corrections (DOC) to your Freedom of Information Act request for DOC’s policy “regarding transgender inmates”, which has been assigned ID Number R001114-052925. Staff has concluded a search and found the attached Gender Classification and Housing policy responsive to the request.

If you consider this response a denial of your FOIA request, please be advised that, under D.C. Official Code § 2-537 and 1 DCMR 412, you may appeal to the Mayor or to the Superior Court of the District of Columbia.

If you elect to appeal to the Mayor, your appeal must be in writing and contain “Freedom of Information Act Appeal” or “FOIA Appeal” in the subject line of the letter as well as on the outside of the envelope.  The appeal must include (1) a copy of the original request, (2) a copy of this letter, (3) a statement of the circumstances, reasons, and or arguments advanced in support of disclosure, and (4) a daytime telephone number, and e-mail and/or U.S. Mail address at which you can be reached.  The appeal must be emailed to foia.appeals@dc.gov<mailto:foia.appeals@dc.gov> or mailed to the Mayor’s Office of Legal Counsel (MOLC) at 1350 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 407, Washington, D.C. 20004. title: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Federal Bureau of Investigation)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
Dear Federal Bureau of Investigation,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to Federal Bureau of Investigation's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Glenn R. Miles FBI Files
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request any FBI records pertaining to Glenn R. Miles, who was killed in the line of duty as a Customs Agent for the U.S. Treasury Department in Arizona on February 21, 1986. This request includes, but is not limited to any FBI lab analysis of Agent Miles' handheld audio recorder, or references to its contents, as well as any 302s or field reports regarding Agent Miles' potential interactions with the alleged drug traffickers who were reportedly involved in his murder. Finally, this request includes any records sent or received by FBI to William Laverty, U.S. Customs Attache at the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City regarding the July 1986 arrest of five Mexican nationals in Hermosillo, Sonora, Mexico who were alleged to have been involved with the slaying.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Cast vote record (CVR) data for the following elections:
1. 2022 Nov Midterm Election
2. 2024 Nov General Election

Specifically, I’m looking for the full anonymized record of votes cast each election generated by the voting system.

In case it is helpful for your reference, you can find an example of these records in REDACTED format at this link on the Arapahoe County webpage: https://www.arapahoevotes.gov/transparency
If you follow the "Redacted Cast Vote Record (CVR)" link on that webpage, it will download a csv file with Arapahoe County's redacted CVR records (this: https://gis.arapahoegov.com/dl_data/cr_voter_data/redacted_cvr/REDACTED_CVR_Export_20241126111830_330948.zip.)

I am requesting these records NOT redacted pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act. Please let me know if you need any further clarification on the type of data that I am requesting.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: RNL contracts and reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All documentation since Jan. 1, 2017 of the university's contracts with Ruffalo, Noel, Levitz (RNL) for the firm's Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive  Analytics services. Specifically, this should include contracts, statements of work, successful RFP response packages, sole source agreements, and data privacy agreements. 

2) All model workbooks for the university's Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive Analytics models. These workbooks, which RNL provides in Excel or other spreadsheet format, contain the model(s)' glossary of variables, market summaries,  and model scores and results,  among other information. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL model workbook.

3) All plans and reports prepared by the university enrollment staff or RNL since Jan. 1, 2017 regarding the university's use of the Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive Analytics model results.  This includes, but is not limited to, plans and reports describing the university's use of model scores to inform student list purchases, targeted communication campaigns, and/or recruiting trips.

4) All end-year conversion reports prepared for the university by RNL since Jan. 1, 2017. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL end-year conversion report.

5) All prospect analysis reports prepared for the university by RNL since Jan. 1, 2017. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL end-year conversion report.

I ask that all fees be waived as intend to use the requested records to further public understanding of public agencies.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. ***     We hope to complete our review of records responsive to your Public Records Request and respond to you by March 23, 2023; however, more time may be necessary.   Your request for WSU records is not confidential. All Public Records Requests are public records. The records responsive to a request may contain names, identifiers, or information about other people (such as employees, former employees, students, former students, or third parties). WSU may send a notice to people named in the records informing them that their name, identifiers, or other information about them will be disclosed under the Public Records Act and provide them sufficient time in which to seek legal counsel to determine whether to file a motion in Whitman County Superior Court to enjoin disclosure. When we send such notices to people named in records, we also provide a copy of the request with the notice.   Please contact this office if you have any questions.   Sincerely,   Public Records Office Washington State University ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Washington State University.

title: Refinery29 Media Request For Title IX Complaint Records

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Refinery29 Media Request For Title IX Complaint Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all Title IX complaints involving The University of Nebraska Lincoln within the past 5 years.

In order to help to determine my status to assess fees, you should know that I am a representative of the news media affiliated with Refinery29 and Vice Media Group, and this request is made as part of news gathering and not for a commercial use.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Molly Longman

communications.communication:

Sincerely,

Robbie Powelson

communications.communication:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello,
Executive Order's 
PROTECTING AMERICAN COMMUNITIES FROM CRIMINAL ALIENS
STRENGTHENING AND UNLEASHING AMERICA’S LAW ENFORCEMENT TO PURSUE CRIMINALS AND PROTECT INNOCENT CITIZENS 

Emails from/with anyone at any federal and local agency, including the United States Attorney General's office, State Attorney General's officer, the Department of Defense, and Immigration and Customs Enforcement, about the executive orders or sanctuary cities

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request - Jeffrey Alan Lincoln
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to video footage from a police intervention, specifically from the body camera worn by the officer(s) and the dashcam of the police vehicles involved. Article:
https://cbsaustin.com/news/nation-world/jeffrey-alan-lincoln-florida-dui-driving-intoxicated-repeat-offender-criminal-history-jail-told-charges-arrests-carried-car-deputy-vodka-bottle-traffic-stop-pickup-truck-drinking-lanes-yelling-marion-brevard-broward-county-breath-test-sheriff-office

Exact date of incident: June 30, 2024
Names of parties involved: Jeffrey Alan Lincoln


I intend to use this footage solely for educational purposes to promote a better understanding of law enforcement procedures and the application of the law.

I understand that there may be associated costs for providing this footage, and I am more than willing to cover any fees incurred. Please inform me about the necessary procedures and the costs involved.

Thank you in advance for your assistance. I trust that this footage will be invaluable for my educational efforts, and I greatly appreciate your cooperation.


Best regards,
George Smith

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

George Smith

communications.subject: FW: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request - Jeffrey Alan Lincoln
communications.communication:
Good morning,
Attached is the invoice for the requested bodycam footage. We must receive payment before the files are processed, we only accept business checks, money orders or cash. Payments can be mailed to the address listed at the bottom of the invoice. Please include a copy of the invoice with your payment. Once payment is received, the files will be processed, and you will receive a download link that will allow you to download the requested footage.
If you have any questions or need to adjust your request, please reply to this email.
Thank you and have a great day!


Sarah Dykstra
Body Worn Camera Technician
Administrative Services Bureau
Office of the Sheriff, Marion County
Desk: (352) 369-6759

communications.subject: Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act Request: Surfline (Middletown Town Clerk)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

The company Surfline has been advertising persistent monitoring of beaches in your town: www.surfline.com. Therefore, I request the following:

1) All instructional materials, presentations and presentation materials (including recorded video and audio, PowerPoint files, prepared remarks, and slides formats), and other guidance on the use of Surfline or Surfzone.ai. This includes A) any notes taken during meetings that discussed the use of Surfline, B) any explanations (whether internally or externally generated) of how Surfline works, and C) any other document that has been used to help explain the use of Surfline, including internal documentation, public relations materials, and executive summaries.

2) A copy of any privacy impact assessments, use policies, standard operating procedures, data retention policies, legal opinions, warranties, non-disclosure agreements, contracts, liability waivers, insurance agreements, Requests for Proposals, Responses to Requests for Proposal, Memorandums of Understanding, Letters of Interest, usage policies, or informal agreements between the department and Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak.

3) A copy of any funding opportunity announcements, grant applications and grantor status/progress reports, reports to legislative bodies, annual reports that mention Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak, as well as audit records, including but not limited to security audits of the software, misuse reports, and reports to oversight bodies.

4) Any digital communications including but not limited to emails and text messages) as well as documents, (including but not limited to PDF, word processing, excel, and slide documents) that mention Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak.

5) Any case reports in which Surfline was used.

6) Any digital communications (including but not limited to emails and text messages) with Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak representatives.

The documents will be used in the course of reporting for 404 Media, an independent tech journalism website (www.404media.co)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jason Koebler

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Request: Operation Stonegarden
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all applications submitted to your agency for funding under Operation Stonegarden. I also request the list of applicants approved for funding under the program. Please limit this request to FY2013 - FY2016.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.


Sincerely,

Grace Raih

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Freedom of Information request, copied below, and originally submitted on Sept. 28, 2017. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response, or if further clarification is needed.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Request: Operation Stonegarden
communications.communication:
Good Afternoon,

Regarding your FOIA request # 2017-FEFO-02310, the request is still out for a search.  Please note that our office and the program office were we sent the records search are both experiencing delays due to staff deployments in response to Hurricanes Harvey, Irma, Maria, Nate and the California wildfires.  We will make every attempt to process and complete your request as soon as possible.  Thank you for your understanding.
Regards,

The FEMA Disclosure Branch

communications.subject: FEMA FOIA 2017-FEFO-02310 - Need More Information - Reply by Dec. 12
communications.communication:
Good Morning Ms. Raih: 
This correspondence is in regards to FEMA FOIA case number 
# 2017-FEFO-02310.   A copy of yourrequest is attached. 
The search produced records totaling several thousands ofpages that may be responsive to the request.  Given the sheer size and the fact that pages may need to beconsulted with other agencies who have equity in them, this may take many monthsto process. 
At this point, would youlike to narrow the scope of your request to only include a particular fiscalyear, or perhaps a short list of locations, that most interest you?  Yourequested the fiscal years and locations below.  Any narrowing of the request would help us to get meaningful records to you in a shorter amount of time. 
FY 13 
FY 14 
FY 15 
FY 16 
Location: all states and territories 
Your case has been placed on a brief hold. Please respond by December 12. Thankyou.
Regards, 
Kevin Hill 
FEMA Disclosure Branch 
FEMA-FOIA@fema.dhs.gov 
202-212-3323

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: City of Novato Communications
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All communications between Kate Gauntlett and Heather Abrams between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Officer Thomas Lyons between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Capt. Jim Correa and Jim Naugle between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robbie Powelson
